                </annotation>
            </sentence>
            <sentence>
                <offset>2565</offset>
                <text>Hypernasal speech was noted.</text>
                <annotation id="45">
                    <infon key="type">webanno.custom.Phenotypes</infon>
                    <infon key="HPOterm">http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/HP_0001611</infon>
                    <location length="17" offset="0"/>
                    <text>Hypernasal speech</text>
                </annotation>
            </sentence>
            <sentence>
                <offset>2594</offset>
                <text>ECG, cardiac ultrasound examination, plasma and urine aminoacidograms, mucopolysaccharide and oligosaccharide screen, bone age, and cytogenetic studies were normal.</text>
            </sentence>
            <sentence>
                <offset>2759</offset>
                <text>The EEG during sleep exhibited mild and diffuse 12–16 Hz activity.</text>
            </sentence>
            <sentence>
                <offset>2826</offset>
                <text>MR examination of the patient's brain revealed enlargement of the Virchow–Robin perivascular spaces, most prominently in the putamen.</text>
                <annotation id="46">
                    <infon key="type">webanno.custom.Phenotypes</infon>
                    <infon key="HPOterm">http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/HP_0012520</infon>
                    <location length="52" offset="47"/>
                    <text>enlargement of the Virchow–Robin perivascular spaces</text>
                </annotation>
            </sentence>
            <sentence>
                <offset>2960</offset>
                <text>A diagnostic hypothesis of Noonan syndrome, based on clinical features, was excluded since no causative mutation was found at the molecular investigation of the PTPN11 gene.</text>
            </sentence>
            <sentence>
                <offset>3135</offset>
                <text>As the patient expressed some features of AAS, although the clinical picture was not completely typical, we proceed with the analysis of the FGD1 gene</text>
            </sentence>
